<TEXT>
residents voted monday to keep gallups 
feisty mayor who once threatened to erect billboards proclaiming 
his city the nations drunkendriving capital in office for the 
remaining 11 months of his term 
the vote to recall mayor ed munoz was 1995 to 2135 opponents 
needed 2246 ballots to oust the 62yearold democrat 
this tells me that the people of gallup want me to continue to 
address the citys alcohol problem said the longtime mayor of 
this city on the edge of a huge indian reservation 
the 50 percent voter turnout was about 15 percent higher than 
expected said city clerk rosalena chavez gallup has 7218 
registered voters 
munoz said he was not upset that 1995 voters wanted him out of 
office 
it tells me that people associated with the liquor industry 
carry a lot of clout and that other people want to continue to live 
in denial he said people that have drinking problems want to 
continue drinking and continue to live in denial 
munoz contends the liquor industry was behind the effort to 
drive him from office because of his campaigns against alcohol 
problems in gallup 
recall organizer linda tiley said she hoped the vote sends a 
message to munoz i hope he sees by the number of votes against 
him that there are a lot of people who disagree with his views 
ms tiley said 
i dont feel that the recall was a total failure just because 
we didnt win she said maybe now people will start to pay 
more attention to city government 
recall organizers had said they were fed up with munoz 
confrontational style and accused him of using his position to 
help friends they noted that he has three times offered to step 
outside to settle differences during city council meetings 
if i had been charged with malfeasance or something like that 
then i wouldnt feel good munoz said earlier but i feel good 
about this 
ms tiley said the mayors proposal in february for billboards 
depicting a car on a road paved with skulls was just the last straw 
the billboards 20 miles west of gallup on the arizona state 
line would have told visitors that lifelong new mexico residents 
have an 86 percent chance of being involved in an alcoholrelated 
traffic accident 
the rest of the country now thinks this is nothing but a town 
of drunks said ms tiley a skincare consultant and parttime 
waitress and bartender 
munoz retracted the billboard proposal saying it was intended 
to get the attention of state legislators after they failed to act 
on liquorlaw reforms the mayor supported he has proposed closing 
all driveup liquor windows and halting sales before 11 am and 
persuaded voters to impose a liquor tax to pay for alcohol 
treatment 
munoz was mayor from 1958 through 1969 and is in the middle of 
his second consecutive twoyear term 
he is challenging state rep dominic ferrari in the june 
democratic primary election and has said he wont seek another 
term as mayor no matter what happened monday 
ms tiley rejected the mayors accusation that the recall was 
backed by the liquor industry she said the campaign organized 
with the help of a mail carrier and three of her coworkers at the 
powder puff beauty salon hasnt taken any money from 
alcoholrelated businesses 
alcohol has nothing to do with it at all ms tiley said 
its his tactics we dont like the way he runs things 
examples she said included munoz interceding on behalf on an 
acquaintance in a zoning matter and three times offering to step 
outside a council meeting to settle a dispute 
the mayor doesnt deny challenging people to fights 
when they make personal slanders against me ill threaten 
them he said 
of allegations he helped his friends munoz said im 
responsive to people in the community as a mayor should be when 
someone needs help i try to help them 
ms tiley contends that gallups liquor problems are no worse 
than any other citys but says munoz by drawing attention to 
drinking has hurt tourism 
gallup population 24600 is on the edge of the west 
virginiasize navajo reservation which sprawls across three states 
and is home to 165000 people alcohol is banned on the 
reservation so navajos who wish to drink legally must go to nearby 
cities like gallup 
the national institute on alcoholism and alcohol abuse found in 
a onetime study that the gallup areas rate of alcoholrelated 
deaths per 100000 people was nearly six times the us average 
from 1975 to 1979 in 1987 the national safety council reported 
that new mexico was the nations per capita leader in traffic 
deaths and that year mckinley county which includes gallup was 
worst among new mexico counties for severe alcoholrelated crashes 
in 1988 city police threw 26222 people in drunk tanks to 
sober up many of them multiple offenders 
</TEXT>
