<TEXT>
the sponsor of the sat is asking a federal court 
to exempt the test from a state law requiring disclosure of 
questions and answers 
the college board said monday that the exemption if granted 
would allow it to administer the scholastic aptitude test more 
often in new york state by holding down the cost of complying with 
the decadeold truthintesting law 
the law requires testmakers to make public test questions 
answers and related research reports such disclosures enable 
students to check their answers or challenge questions they believe 
are flawed or biased 
new york and california are the only two states with 
truthintesting laws but since new yorks law was passed test 
makers have voluntarily extended its provisions to testtakers in 
all 50 states 
the boards request for an injunction was filed monday in 
syracuse joining with the board was the educational testing 
service of princeton nj which administers the scholastic 
aptitude test and numerous other standardized tests 
if the injunction is granted disclosures of test questions and 
answers will no longer be mandatory but board spokesman fred 
moreno said the testmaker would continue to voluntarily disclose 
tests administered on the four existing new york test dates 
the board would then add two new opportunities in december and 
january each year for new yorkers to take the sat there would also 
be additional dates for new yorkers to take the graduate record 
examination and the test of english as a foreign language but 
tests taken on new dates would not be disclosed afterwards 
in effect the college board said that would mean new yorkers 
would have the same number of opportunities to take the tests as 
students in most other states 
the board reduced the number of test dates in new york shortly 
after truthintesting was enacted claiming that it had to do so 
in order to keep the cost of the exam down 
blair horner a spokesman for the new york public interest 
research group which successfully lobbied for truthintesting 
said the college boardets suit reveals their true character to 
gouge students in order to maximize their profits 
but test publishers insisted they were not trying to subvert 
truthintesting 
we do not want to turn the clock back on test disclosure 
said greg anrig president of ets in a telephone interview he 
added that he had gone on record on numerous occasions in support 
of truthintesting 
consumer advocate ralph nader called the lawsuit a big 
mistake this lawsuit will make the standardized testing industry 
fraud a nationally visible issue for public discussion 
cinthia schuman executive director of fairtest a cambridge 
mass group critical of standardized tests called the action by 
the college board and ets hypocrisy 
why should your right to disclosure of a test depend on the 
date that you take it she said 
the sat is taken by about 16 million collegebound high school 
students each year and approximately 200000 new york students 
the way was paved for mondays action when a federal court in 
january ruled that disclosure provisions of new yorks 
truthintesting law conflicted with federal copyright law that 
case involved the mcat a medical school entrance exam 
</TEXT>
