<TEXT>
after 15 years of fratricidal carnage 
living in beirut has been reduced to survival real life as other 
people know it is on hold 
peace has become more important than life electricity more 
important than the future and butane gas more important than 
completing the school year says talal salman owner of the 
leftist daily assafir 
the lebanese whose disparate factions are sponsored by such as 
iran israel libya syria and iraq appear to have an insatiable 
appetite for killing each other 
no one knows for sure how many people have been killed or maimed 
since the sectarian civil war began on april 13 1975 
estimates of the number killed range up to 150000 doctors at 
the american university hospital say a total of 200000 killed or 
wounded probably is close 
in the latest warwithinawar christians are fighting 
christians 
rebel gen michel aouns soldiers and samir geageas militiamen 
are battling for control of the 310squaremile christian enclave 
north and east of beirut where twothirds of the 15 million 
lebanese christians live 
even the remarkable resilience of the lebanese has been tested 
to its limits by the long war factional feuding two israeli 
invasions and countless air strikes 
for most of the last year beirut has had little or no water and 
electricity civilian life has been conducted largely underground 
in basements and subterranean parking lots used as shelters from 
artillery fire 
what future is there any more asked antoine mousa a 
christian civilian one works only to make enough money to cover 
the expenses of repairing damage 
fadi koukou who at 14 is one year younger than the war has had 
only three months of schooling since march 1989 most of his time 
has been spent in shelters 
i dont think ill be able to concentrate on my studies if 
classes resume he said i havent held a book for a long long 
time 
koukou who lives in the devastated ashrafiyeh district of 
christian east beirut said he envied youngsters in europe and the 
united states because at least they dont have to spend hours 
filling canisters with water and lug them up five flights of stairs 
because the elevators out 
flashes remain of prewar lebanon when beirut bustled with 
vitality and a phoenician gaudiness that made it the last of the 
great levantine cities the playground of the middle east 
lady cochrane who was yvonne sursock when she married an irish 
baronet still holds elegant dinner parties in her colonnaded home 
in east beirut as she did when she was the queen of beirut society 
before the war 
it is her way of showing contempt for the danger and insanity 
around her 
even so lady cochrane whose greek orthodox family has produced 
generations of lebanese notables has stored her art works for 
safekeeping 
a briton invited for dinner a few weeks ago while an artillery 
duel raged said she sat at the head of the table as family 
