<TEXT>
hundreds of police some in riot gear took to 
the streets of chinas capital to prevent unrest on the anniversary 
of the start of last springs prodemocracy movement 
they succeeded a lone protester was arrested sunday other 
expressions of dissent were discouraged by the heavy police 
presence 
a year ago sunday former communist party chief hu yaobang died 
hu was ousted from power in 1987 for failing to stop student 
demonstrations and students mourning his death used the occassion 
to criticize the leadership and push for democratic reform and an 
end to official corruption 
for seven weeks beijing streets were filled with crowds of up 
to 1 million people demanding the resignation of unpopular leaders 
and more say in how they live their lives 
it all ended when troops invaded the city on june 34 killing 
hundreds of prodemocracy demonstrators with automatic weapons fire 
and driving students from tiananmen square the countrys symbolic 
seat of power 
this spring beijing is a different city students say protests 
are unlikely because of heavy police surveillance and the certainty 
that anyone who tries to organize a demonstration will be arrested 
in addition thousands of people who took part in last years 
demonstrations are thought to still be in jail without charges and 
some protest leaders have fled the country 
in anticipation of sundays anniversary police set up 
checkpoints at several intersections near the university area in 
northwestern beijing and officers carrying rifles with bayonets 
drawn patrolled the square 
the square was open to the public sunday unlike on april 1 and 
5 when police sealed it to block feared protests overseas 
dissidents had urged people to silently stroll through the square 
on those days in honor of those killed last june 
sundays only incident occurred when a man in his 30s began to 
pin on his sleeve white paper flowers a traditional sign of 
mourning streamers from the flowers read to mourn hu yaobang 
and heroes who die for democracy and liberty 
police quickly arrested the man who told onlookers he was a 
scientist from the southern province of guizhou and had come to 
beijing to mourn our great general secretary hu 
he carried suitcases and said he had come to beijing with 
everything he owned in anticipation of being arrested 
