the government will sponsor a threeyear 29 
million research project aimed at reducing or preventing the 
elderly from becoming physically frail two federal agencies say 
the national institute on aging and the national center for 
nursing research said sites in eight states will be used for the 
ficsit project which stands for frailty and injuries 
cooperative studies of intervention techniques 
more than 1500 volunteers are expected to participate the 
program will feature exercise ranging from the oriental practice 
of tai chi to aerobic dance education to make older people aware 
of accident risks and rehabilitation to improve physical 
conditioning 
millions of older people lack strength mobility balance and 
endurance and are therefore susceptible to serious falls nursing 
home admissions and a loss of independence according to the nia 
the new trials highlight the fact that frailty and injuries 
are not the inevitable outcome of aging said nia director dr t 
franklin williams instead they are problems for which we have 
now found some very viable solutions 
more than 32 percent of people over age 75 cannot climb stairs 
40 percent are unable to walk two blocks 7 percent cannot walk 
across a small room and 22 percent cannot lift 10 pounds the nia 
said fortytwo percent of nursing home residents cannot get out of 
a chair without help 
