two men convicted of a famous london jewel 
robbery who want to be moved from a british prison to one in this 
country lost a supreme court appeal today 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that spared the 
us attorney general from adopting rules that could have led to 
the prison transfers 
jerome scalise and arthur rachel are us citizens convicted in 
the 36 million holdup of a london jewelry store in 1980 their 
haul included the famous marlborough diamond 
authorities said the jewels have not been recovered 
scalise and rachel began serving 15year prison terms aug 6 
1984 they are eligible for release in july 1993 
the united states and great britain ratified a treaty in 1985 
that permits prisoners in each nation to be transferred to their 
homeland 
scalise and rachel sued in federal court in the united states 
seeking to compel former attorney general edwin meese iii to 
transfer them home and to adopt guidelines governing prisoner 
transfers between great britain and the united states 
meese and his successor attorney general dick thornburgh 
refused to adopt such rules or grant the wish of the two men to 
return home 
a federal judge ordered the adoption of the guidelines but that 
ruling was overturned last december by the 7th us circuit court 
of appeals 
the appeals court acknowledged that the treaty is intended to 
help rehabilitate prisoners by letting them return to their 
homeland and be closer to family and friends but it ruled that 
such decisions should be left to the attorney general without 
judicial secondguessing 
the case is scalise vs thornburgh 891478 
