<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to order the 
government to reveal the names and addresses of retired or disabled 
federal workers 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by an 
organization seeking to use the information to recruit new members 
in its campaign for increased benefits for retirees 
the national association of retired federal employees used to 
have an agreement with the federal office of personnel management 
that helped the associations drive for new members 
the agency from 1979 to 1981 permitted the association to send 
information packets to newly retired federal workers through an 
independent mailing service the association was not given the 
names or addresses until recipients of the packets expressed an 
interest in joining 
after the office of personnel management ended the arrangement 
the association sought to obtain the names and addresses under the 
freedom of information act 
a federal judge ruled in favor of the association but the us 
circuit court of appeals here overturned that ruling last july 
the appeals court said revealing the names and addresses of 
retired and disabled workers would violate their privacy 
the appeals court said that if the association is allowed to 
have the names there would be no basis under the freedom of 
information act to withhold the names from others who seek them 
any business or fundraising organization for which such 
individuals might be an attractive market could get from the 
government at nominal cost a list of prime sales prospects to 
solicit the appeals court said business people will not 
overlook an opportunity to get cheaply from the government what 
otherwise comes dearly 
by contrast the appeals court said the retirees association 
failed to show there is a public interest in revealing the names 
and addresses even a modest privacy interest outweighs nothing 
every time the appeals court said 
the association said the appeals court misinterpreted the 
freedom of information act a 1966 law aimed at curtailing 
government secrecy the association said congress intended that 
such lists be provided unless release would constitute a clearly 
unwarranted invasion of privacy 
justice department lawyers urged the high court to reject the 
associations appeal 
the case is national association of retired federal employees 
vs newman 891098 
