<TEXT>
the bush administration and the national 
wildlife federation clashed before the supreme court monday over 
what it takes to prove an individual has been harmed by opening 
federal lands to commercial development 
the justice department asked the high court to reverse a june 
ruling from the us appeals court for the district of columbia 
the ruling gives environmentalists potentially sweeping power to 
prevent the restricted public lands from being opened to mining and 
mineral exploration 
the appellate ruling said the federation may sue the interior 
department over the governments plans to change the status of 180 
million acres of public land in the west and alaska 
the appellate came after the federation presented affidavits 
from members who said they use some of the land for recreation 
peggy k peterson said the bureau of land managements decision 
to allow mining in the vicinity of south passgreen mountain 
wyo has adversely affected her recreational use and aesthetic 
enjoyment of the federal lands 
in particular the south passgreen mountain area of wyoming 
has been opened up to the staking of mining claims and oil and gas 
leasing an action which threatens aesthetic beauty and wildlife 
habitat potential of these lands she said in an affidavit 
federation spokesman david alberswerth said monday that a high 
court decision against the environmentalists would prevent them 
from challenging reclassification of land initiated by the reagan 
administration in 1985 following a policy instituted by 
theninterior secretary james g watt in 1981 
it will severely constrain the opportunity for environmental 
groups such as ours to take the government to court alberswerth 
said 
the federation said the reagan administration violated the 
federal law by opening the land to development without following 
procedures in the 1976 federal land policy and management act such 
as conducting environmental impact statements 
the issue before the supreme court is whether peterson and the 
federations 45 million members have standing in the case or the 
right to sue based on damage to their recreational use and 
aesthetic enjoyment of the lands 
john g roberts jr of the justice department told the justices 
that peterson and others have been too vague in explaining the harm 
and the specific area where the harm has occurred 
he said they should be required to show damages on specific 
tracts of land where commercial development has been approved 
