<TEXT>
bush administration is examining ideas for 
broad changes in the banking system but is months away from 
deciding on specific proposals officials said monday 
the treasury department has expanded an ongoing study of federal 
deposit insurance to include a look at restructuring the regulatory 
bureaucracy and at mixing commercial banking with the insurance and 
securities industries officials said 
savings and loan legislation enacted last august requires 
treasury to complete the deposit insurance study by february it is 
focused on ways to limit taxpayers liability for the insurance and 
on removing incentives from the system that encourage unwarranted 
risktaking by insured institutions 
administration officials also have long discussed modernizing 
the financial system by relaxing the restrictions that have 
separated commercial banking from the securities business since 
enactment of the 1933 glasssteagall act 
the effort which is being combined with the deposit insurance 
study has been intensified by the prospect of increased 
competition from foreign institutions after the economic 
unification of europe in 1992 
the administration also is reviewing a recent congressional 
report that predicted the savings and loan bailout will fall short 
requiring billions of dollars more from taxpayers 
the treasury department is broadening the study to 
consider other problems in the financial industry the savings and 
loan situation certainly demands attention white house spokesman 
marlin fitzwater said monday i think its fair to say that 
treasury is looking at the broad regulatory aspects of banking 
officials denied however that the administration was settling 
on a number of controversial proposals reported in mondays 
editions of the washington post among them were 
cutting the 100000peraccount deposit insurance in half and 
limiting depositors to one insured account 
merging the banking and sampl industries and eliminating the 
treasury departments office of thrift supervision 
combining the insurance funds for banks and thrift 
institutions thereby forcing banks to help pay for the sampl bailout 
we dont have any conclusions at the moment the study is 
certainly a long way from being completed fitzwater said 
treasury spokeswoman desiree tuckersorini said the deposit 
insurance review is in its early stages and the administration has 
no preconceived ideas about how the system should be changed 
she said the administration last year rejected merging the bank 
and sampl insurance funds and we have no proposal to do that now 
at this time we dont see any reason to abolish the thrift 
office she added 
but she also said that the department hasnt rejected any ideas 
either only that the administration believes this year is too soon 
after passage of the sampl law to act on major banking legislation 
for next year who knows at this point its way too early to 
determine she said 
deputy treasury secretary john e robson in a private speech 
earlier this month to the independent bankers association of 
america revealed that the department had widened the scope of its 
approach 
the treasury study is not going to focus on deposit insurance 
in a vacuum robson said we are taking a comprehensive 
approach including consideration of the financial activities 
in which institutions engage and the regulatory structure 
lobbing groups objected strongly to some of the ideas floated in 
the posts story 
floating a proposal to cut back existing levels of deposit 
insurance is unfortunate said kenneth guenther executive vice 
president of the independent bankers association of america it 
further weakens confidence in the financial industry and if 
implemented would further weaken the thrift industry and 
consequently increase the cost of the sampl bailout 
robert dugger chief economist of the american bankers 
association said merging the bank and sampl insurance funds would 
raise public concerns about bank safety 
its a formula for financial disaster he said you 
cant burden the bank insurance fund with the thrift crisis its 
not designed for that and would collapse under the weight 
</TEXT>
