<TEXT>
the government on monday banned eight 
militant moslem organizations in kashmir and closed two local 
newspapers in its latest effort to contain unrest in the disputed 
territory 
the press trust of india news agency said one of the 
organizations outlawed was the jammukashmir liberation front 
which is leading the bloody independence campaign in the northern 
area bordering pakistan 
the two newspapers closed are in srinagar kashmirs main city 
and the center of the separatist campaign 
a government statement said the urdu language newspapers aftab 
and alsafa had published materials to incite the public 
earlier monday witnesses accused indian soldiers of brutalizing 
suspected militants during housetohouse searches at least 33 
people were arrested the searches came on the 10th day of a 
24hour curfew that has restricted civilians to their homes 
in one district troops were seen forcing a group of men to 
perform squats a kneebend exercise with heavy stones on their 
backs 
none of them are militants said one witness but this 
will make them militants we thought the indian army was 
disciplined but we were wrong 
he and other witnesses all of whom spoke on condition of 
anonymity said they were too far away to know what provoked the 
action 
the government imposed a roundtheclock curfew april 6 after 
three people were kidnapped by moslem militants whose seek 
secession of the kashmir valley from hindudominated india all 
three hostages were shot to death when the government failed to 
respond to the kidnappers demands of freedom for three jailed 
comrades 
since then residential areas of srinagar at the far northern 
tip of india have been under constant curfew as troops fan out to 
search for suspects 
on monday the government announced a twohour relaxation of 
curfew in the civil lines shopping district witnesses said most 
shops in civil lines did not open because the shop owners live in 
downtown srinagar where curfew was not lifted 
the insurgency in the kashmir valley has claimed at least 270 
lives since the government cracked down on the moslem movement on 
jan 20 most of the victims have died in confrontations between 
security forces and the militants 
the independence movement has also escalated tensions between 
india and pakistan which have fought two wars over the valley 
since both counties gained independence from britain in 1947 
the hindu ruler of the moslemdominated kashmir province opted 
to join india although other moslemmajority provinces went to 
islamic pakistan 
a moslem secession movement has grown in recent years because of 
complaints the region was being ignored by new delhi 
india accuses pakistan of fomenting the insurgency an 
accusation pakistan denies 
