<TEXT>
a juvenile facing a possible death sentence in 
alabama lost his final court battle to avoid extradition monday 
when the supreme court refused to hear his appeal 
the 17yearold boy identified in court proceedings only by the 
initials om is charged with arson and murder in the may 1988 
death of 14monthold tamal jackson who was killed when a firebomb 
exploded inside an apartment at a gadsden ala housing project 
om has been fighting extradition since his arrest by district 
of columbia authorities in december 1988 his battle has attracted 
widespread attention because of its focus on capital punishment for 
juveniles and southern justice for blacks 
james a hedgspeth district attorney for etowah county ala 
said the supreme courts refusal to hear the case removes the last 
legal obstacle to the youths return to alabama to face the 
juvenile petition charging him with arson and murder 
the etowah county district court will determine whether om 
will be certified to stand trial as an adult a move that could 
subject him to the death penalty if convicted 
oms lawyers argued unsuccessfully in washington courts that 
his extradition would violate the district governments ban on 
capital punishment 
they also contended that om who is black could not get a 
fair trial from the predominantly white judicial system in etowah 
county where both his father and another relative died in police 
custody 
two of oms uncles 32yearold yul devoe guice and an 
18yearold identified only by the initials st also were charged 
with arson and murder in the death of the jackson infant 
st was arrested by district of columbia authorities last 
summer and has also been fighting extradition to alabama 
</TEXT>
