<TEXT>
the bush administration is allowing south 
african iron and steel into the united states despite a 1986 
economic sanction designed to force an end to apartheid the state 
department said monday 
most of the controversial imports are ferroalloys strategic 
commodities never intended by congress to be banned under the law 
said department spokeswoman margaret d tutwiler 
the administrations definition of steel was upheld in a federal 
court in 1987 and certain prefabricated products that contain steel 
are not included in the definition of steel she said 
this administration will continue to enforce fully all 
provisions of the comprehensive antiapartheid act ms tutwiler 
said this is an old issue that has been thoroughly reviewed by 
the treasury department 
another us official requesting anonymity said some 
prefabricated items such as toasters and some ferroalloys had been 
imported the official said the volume of imports was not readily 
available 
the new york times quoting commerce department officials 
reported saturday that more than 900000 tons of south african iron 
and steel products worth at least 350 million had entered the 
united states despite the sanctions 
nothwithstanding any other provision of law no iron or steel 
produced in south africa may be imported into the united states 
the law says 
the times said treasury department lawyers had defined steel 
to exclude fabricated steel products such as girders beams and 
plates used in the construction of bridges 
however rep john bryant dtexas took issue with the 
interpretation 
there is no excuse for the administration to allow even one 
ounce much less billions of pounds of such products to enter the 
united states bryant told the times 
a treasury department official told the associated press on 
monday that ferroalloys were always outside the scope of the law 
and that the department intended to screen out prefabricated 
products containing steel 
but the official said the appeals court for the court of 
international trade ruled against the department the official 
who spoke on condition of anonymity said such imports were very 
minor about 1 percent of the volume of ferroalloys 
our enforcement is very strict the official said there 
is no reason for alarm 
the law passed by congress over president reagans veto also 
prohibits new lending and investment bans flights to and from 
south africa and prohibits american imports of south african coal 
textiles uranium farm products and gold coins 
the reagan administration called repeatedly for an end to racial 
segregation in south africa however it opposed sanctions saying 
blacks would suffer if the countrys economy were hurt 
