<TEXT>
the bush administration said monday it would 
not forbid american companies from offering special purchasing 
incentives to win contracts for military sales aboard though it 
will not encourage thoce incentives either 
a white house statement said that incentives known in military 
circles as offsets have become a common feature in the 
international arms trade an offset is a requirement that the 
selling company buy a certain amount of goods and services in the 
buying country 
the decision whether to engage in offsets and the 
responsibility for negotiating and implementing offset 
arrangements resides with the companies involved the white 
house said in a policy statement issued under president bushs name 
the administration said no agency of the us government will 
encourage offsets or commit us firms to offset deals 
moreover it said that no us government funds will be used to 
finance offsets in security assistance deals except in accordance 
with currently established policies and procedures 
white house press secretary marlin fitzwater said the government 
views offsets for military exports as economically inefficient 
and market distorting 
one case of offsets cited by the pentagon involved the recent 
purchase of 11 airborne radar warning and control planes from 
boeing by britain and france in an 18 billion deal 
the two countries demanded an offset from boeing of 130 percent 
meaning that the manufacturer would have to buy more than 23 
billion in goods and services from britain and france 
such an arrangement puts the us company in the role of a 
middleman for selling the foreign countries goods if they have 
