<TEXT>
argentinas public works 
minister roberto dromi said monday that about 80000 public 
employees will be retired or laid off by the end of the month as an 
austerity measure 
government workers past retirement age or within two years of 
retirement are affected employees who hold two jobs in the state 
sector must give up one employees who are in position to be 
retired are going to receive their pensions and be retired dromi 
said in an interview broadcast by radio rivadavia 
such action has been rare in argentina since the late president 
juan peron came to power in 1946 peron entrenched himself by 
creating or expanding state companies in part to spur employment 
and improve working conditions peronist provincial governments 
still expand public rolls during bad economic times 
argentina returned to democracy in december 1983 after nearly 
eight years of harsh military rule but the economy has been in 
constant trouble for decades 
dromi said the public sector amounts to about 3 million of the 
12 million total workforce argentinas total population is about 
31 million 
the public administration is absolutely too big alberto 
kohan a key aide to president carlos menem told reporters 
the government announced on march 4 that it was planning job 
cutbacks and tax increases to slash the budget deficit by 2 
billion it put no figure on forced retirements and layoffs until 
dromis comments 
retirement clauses in collective bargaining contracts vary from 
ages 55 to 65 
a recession has idled up to 15 percent of the workforce and 
shrunk wages for many workers to 100 or less a month many rely on 
overtime or a second job to make ends meet 
initial comments from labor leaders were cautious victor de 
gennaro secretarygeneral of the 145000member association of 
state workers said the measure wont serve to lower public 
spending because more employees would be suspended with pay than 
retired 
the retirements wont improve the functioning of the state on 
the contrary capable people will be lost he told the private 
news agency noticias argentinas 
union leaders supported menem a peronist during his election 
campaign last year however many have protested since he took 
office last july that his policies of budget austerity and economic 
reform have hurt union members 
menem drastically increased public service rates freed wages 
and prices opened the oil industry to foreign investment and put 
state companies up for sale in an attempt to reduce the fiscal 
deficit 
the deficit for years covered by the central banks printing 
currency is a prime cause of inflation that soared by 95 percent 
in march and 20266 percent the past 12 months 
the forced retirements are almost certain to provoke a labor 
reaction unions representing oilfield and train workers bank 
clerks and others have staged strikes or job actions this year to 
protest layoffs 
shrinking the public payroll is seen as a major test of whether 
menem is willing to take on organized labor long the backbone of 
the peronist party analysts and critics say such a confrontation 
is essential and unavoidable 
the labor ministry this year has asked labor courts to withdraw 
the legal status of unions that strike for political rather than 
economic reasons 
last week about 70 members of the brotherhood of locomotive 
engineers were fired for participating in a strike the ministry 
ruled illegal 
</TEXT>
