<TEXT>
despite a merchants strike that shut down 
the citys famed chinatown the board of supervisors voted monday 
to tear down a quakedamaged freeway the merchants consider a vital 
link to their community 
almost 1200 shops restaurants and professional offices all 
but five small businesses signed up to take part in the 
threehour shutdown said protest organizer rose pak of the chinese 
chamber of commerce 
many of the business people attended the meeting at which the 
supervisors considered a proposal by mayor art agnos to consider 
replacing the elevated embarcadero freeway with either a surface or 
underground road 
the board voted 65 to accept agnos proposal the state 
department of transportation previously agreed to abide by the 
supervisors vote on the stateowned freeway 
supervisor angela alioto said the vote means the freeway that 
runs along the waterfront will have to be torn down but pak vowed 
to continue the fight and hold state officials to a plan to repair 
the road 
the strike began at 130 pm and chinatown came to a grinding 
halt most stores closed with shopkeepers taking their goods off 
the sidewalks 
the usual shouldertoshoulder pedestrian traffic in the heart 
of chinatown went away the noise of car horns was replaced by the 
sound of chimes blowing in the breeze 
we just got in to chinatown and already got kicked out of two 
shops said michael kiriazis a businessman from portland ore 
just as the strike began 
hundreds of chinatown business people and residents climbed 
aboard buses that shuttled them to city hall 
it has stood empty since a 71magnitude earthquake shook 
northern california six months ago killing 68 people cracking 
concrete columns supporting the waterfront roadway 
agnos recently proposed tearing down the elevated freeway long 
considered an eyesore as well as an easy entrance for drivers into 
chinatown and the restaurants of north beach and tourist 
attractions at fishermans wharf in its place the mayor suggested 
building an underground road that he believes would be safer from 
earthquakes and more aesthetically pleasing 
but pak and others such as supervisor tom hsieh contend 
repairing the existing freeway would be better because it would get 
business traffic back into the economically depressed chinatown 
area sooner and cheaper 
the agnos plan calls for expenditures of about 120 million 
mostly in federal funds over four years repairing the old 
freeway however would cost the state transportation department 
about 32 million to wrap the structures support columns in 
2inchthick steel jackets making it able to withstanding an 
83magnitude quake under that plan the freeway would reopen by 
october 
time is essential to chinatown merchants while deputy mayor 
james ho estimated business in that area is down by 8 percent pak 
placed the loss closer to 30 percent for touristdependent 
businesses and 20 percent for those relying on local residents 
she said the community is united behind the repair plan 
this is the first time in 205 years the chinese community has 
shut down their businesses to protest pak said 
while chinatown initiated its protest action the san francisco 
chronicle ran a column by 1990 pulitzer prizewinning architecture 
critic allan temko headlined freeway must go for the city to 
thrive 
temko argued for a buried freeway and said san francisco could 
once again be the beau ideal of a civilized american metropolis 
as it was before the freeway transformed one of the loveliest 
waterfronts in the world into one of the most obscene 
