<TEXT>
laws mandating the use of recycled 
newsprint will slow progress toward recycling rather than speed it 
up the president and chief executive of the hearst corp said 
april 11 
frank bennack jr who is chairman of an american newspaper 
publishers association task force on recycling said such laws 
could cause the severe disruption of the newspaper and newsprint 
production industries 
society cannot legislate solutions to what are basically 
economic problems he said only a free market can produce 
solutions to economic problems that are effective and efficient 
bennack received the rochester institute of technologys isaiah 
thomas award for outstanding contributions to the newspaper 
publishing industry 
about 35 percent of all used newsprint is recycled bennack said 
there is obviously much room for improvement in those 
statistics he said and there is agreement that it can and 
will be done 
but bennack said the conversion must be voluntary 
there is a shortage of recycled newsprint because most paper 
mills are not equipped to handle recycling bennack said 
laws mandating recycling such as those in california and 
connecticut could cause imbalances and shortages in other parts of 
the country he said bennack said he also opposes such regulations 
in principle because regulated newsprint is typical of a 
nondemocratic society 
instead bennack said there should be more voluntary agreements 
by publishers to increase their use of recycled newsprint he 
called for efforts by the states to make used newsprint available 
and encourage the construction of recycling plants 
</TEXT>
