<TEXT>
the bradenton herald reported that a 
meeting between representatives of the paper and four city council 
members april 9 to discuss newspaper rack regulations may have 
violated the states open government law 
the council members met with herald publisher dorothy ridings 
and four other employees at the newspapers offices at the heralds 
invitation the meeting was called to discuss how area newspapers 
could address the councils concerns about newspaper rack placement 
and appearance said general manager robert turner one of those 
present 
in december herald representatives requested that the council 
delay voting on an ordinance regulating newspaper racks city 
officials gave the newspaper three months to come up with possible 
alternatives to the proposed ordinance 
floridas sunshine law prohibits public officials from 
conducting business in private meetings 
the states courts have held that the law applies to any 
gathering of two or more members of the same board and that it is 
applicable when board members are discussing any matter on which 
action might be taken 
ridings said she did not realize at the time that the meeting 
might have violated the law 
if anyone should have realized it i should have she said 
all i can do is apologize to the public and our colleagues for 
putting us and them in an embarrassing situation 
council members said they thought the media had been invited to 
the session and that there was no intent to break the law 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
attorneys for mcdonalds corp have written 
letters to newspapers advising them not to publish advertisements 
from an anticholesterol crusader who launched a national campaign 
earlier this month 
