a judge on april 6 ordered 25 newspapers and 
television stations to give police all film and photographs of a 
march 31 antitax riot in london 
a dozen organizations immediately opposed the order two said 
they were willing to hand over what they published and the 
remaining 11 neither opposed nor consented 
judge neil denison issued the order after a day of legal 
argument ruling the film would help police and that it was in 
the overriding public interest 
however he said in other cases the public interest may be 
better served by allowing the news media to report events freely 
and each case should be decided on its merits 
it is right as has been argued that the court should not 
automatically or routinely grant such orders denison said it 
should not be seen to be rubberstamping such applications 
the news organizations reacted angrily 
if we are seen to be a potential arm of the state journalists 
are going to be targets of the rioters said tvam news director 
jeff berliner 
geoffrey shaw lawyer for the bbc and tvam argued there had 
been 2750 police officers at the poll tax demonstration 
they should not require the media to be their eyes and ears 
if they want film it is reasonable to expect them to take it 
themselves shaw said 
the riot broke out after 40000 had gathered for a peaceful 
demonstration to protest the new poll tax by prime minister 
margaret thatchers government 
