<TEXT>
only in america could an irish bandleader 
in a town of polish immigrants transform that most hokey of ethnic 
music into sounds worthy of carnegie hall 
you see polkas dont come just with kielbasa anymore 
slush down some beer and polish sausage thats all some 
people see when they think of the polka said fred hudy 
president of the international polka association in chicago 
were trying to get rid of that image 
theyre definitely out of the closet now said ian dove 
spokesman for the national academy of recording arts and sciences 
which added a polka category to the grammys five years ago 
the jimmy sturr orchestra is riding the new wave of polka 
popularity winning the grammy four straight years sturr has 
played at new yorks carnegie hall six times the only polka band 
to perform that much at the celebrated concert auditorium 
once relegated to the stomping grounds of local sausage fests or 
to sunday morning radio broadcasts the polka is following latin 
american and cajun into the musical mainstream 
its big business said sturr 42 an irish bandleader who 
lives in the orange county village of florida about 30 miles 
northwest of new york city 
his 10piece orchestra has recorded 76 albums 75 polka and one 
country on his starr records label which he started in 1964 the 
label records other polka country and ethnic groups including 
bobby vinton 
getting its own grammy category has completed the legitimization 
of a musical form once thought squarer than the square dance until 
1985 polka music was lumped into the catchall folk category dove 
said 
it was felt that polka was a form of music unto itself he 
said similarly the grammy trustees created separate categories 
for reggae tropical latin and mexicanamerican music in recent 
years 
sturr started his first band when he was 11 though irish he 
was surrounded by polishamericans who made up fourfifths of his 
hometowns population sturr grew up with the polka and fell in 
love with the music he began recording and touring with his polka 
band in the musical maelstrom of the 1960s when most people viewed 
the polka as a dance confined to the bowling alley crowds of 
milwaukee or buffalo 
its moved out of that ethnic category sturr said now 
everybody enjoys the polka when i was a kid and somebody said 
hey what kind of band do you have id be embarrassed to say im 
in a polka band 
minnesota gov rudy perprich declared 1990 the year of the 
polka thousands attend polka festivals each year in minnesota 
which claims to have the granddaddy of all polka fests in 
gibbon minn 
like cajun and country the shrill brass and reedy woodwinds of 
some polka styles revolve around the accordion which is enjoying 
its own return from corn purgatory 
its a happy music its a snappy music hudy said your 
feet automatically tap 
several rock groups have transformed themselves into new wave 
polka bands turning out what sturr calls punk polka one such 
band rotundi has scored a parody polka hit with polka till you 
puke 
in the united states the polka is most closely associated with 
polishamericans yet the polka invented in 1830 by a peasant 
girl in bohemia now part of czechoslovakia never was popular in 
poland even though it was influenced by polish styles of music and 
dance 
as the polka swept through europe in the 1830s and 40s poland 
was trying to regain its independence from russia other europeans 
considered the polka a twostep with a hop thrown in a dance of 
sympathy for polands oppression but the poles felt the polka 
mocked the way polish women danced said charles keil american 
studies professor at the state university of buffalo 
europeans had a general fascination with poland as a 
struggling country whose borders had been violated thats 
where polka dots came from everybody was naming things after the 
polka said keil whose book polka happiness is being 
published by temple university 
from europe the polka traveled around the world it became 
paraguays national dance while american indians out west adopted 
a form of polka in the 1860s 
those indians think of the polka as their traditional music 
nowadays keil said 
while sturrs polishamerican polkas win grammys 
mexicanamerican bands in southern texas are producing the most 
innovative polka music today keil said 
the mexicanamerican style mixes latin and polka rhythms while 
sturrs eastern polish style relies on woodwinds accordions and a 
frantic beat in the midwest the slower german polka with its 
brassy oompahs is popular while plucky banjos highlight country 
polka styles 
polkas must be written in twofour time two quarter notes per 
measure a tempo which gives the music its dancy beat the songs 
can range from the toofat polka with its whimsical chorus 
i dont want her you can have her shes too fat for me to 
the more sentimental did you ever fall in love polka from one 
of sturrs albums 
songwriter steve lopuch has contributed three songs to sturrs 
records including titles on his 1988 grammy album i remember 
warsaw and this years winner all in my love for you 
lopuchs source material ranges from nursery rhymes in the 
crooked man polka to allamerican denim in the blue jeans 
polka 
when these people came the irish polish lithuanians 
germans italians they didnt have nothing said lopuch a 
retired dairy farmer in the montgomery county town of florida 30 
miles west of albany not to be confused with the village of 
florida where sturr grew up they planned to stay a few years 
make some money and go back but most didnt go back they stayed 
and so did their music 
lopuch has written about a dozen polkas based on nursery rhymes 
which he hopes to have recorded by sturrs orchestra or some other 
polka band 
im hoping grandparents will buy it for their grandchildren so 
they dont listen only to rock lopuch said 
keil has similar hopes that more young people will turn to 
polka local polka fests are dying out because a younger 
generation has not come along and gotten into the dancing of it in 
any big way he said 
he predicts there will be a revival of polka dancing its so 
good its eating drinking dancing partying music because it 
survived so long despite rock n roll despite tv because some 
fanatic people wont give it up its a matter of young people 
getting really bored with postpunk nonsense people will see that 
community dancing is a powerful thing 
