<TEXT>
doreen edwards third rejection letter arrived 
earlier this month 
i was disappointed but not squashed flat she said about the 
return of her third manuscript from mills and boon publisher of 
romantic fiction 
hoping to hone her talent edward recently came down from her 
home in wales husband grudgingly in tow to attend a mills and 
boon writers workshop at the london book fair 
mills and boon britains equivalent of harlequin in the united 
states depends heavily on selfstarters who are willing to slave 
over a typewriter between household chores or holding down a job 
the company receives 5000 unsolicited manuscripts a year and 
editorial director frances whitehead crisscrosses the country to 
dispense encouragement and criticism to her authors 
more than 100 people mostly women recently turned up to hear 
whitehead and one of her bestselling authors sally wentworth 
dispense nuggets of advice 
among the pearls of wisdom for romance writers 
disease isnt taboo but messy disease is 
the best time to submit manuscripts is midjanuary after the 
prechristmas deluge 
the hero should have a ruthless streak women dont fantasize 
about apologizers 
submit more than one title chances are your first choice has 
been used before 
the formula for a mills and boon novel is that the couple 
meets on page one and after 50000 words they have decided to spend 
the rest of their lives together its up to the writer to fill in 
the rest whitehead said 
mills and boon has been publishing romantic fiction since 1908 
when gerald mills and charles boon founded the company last year 
it sold 15 million books in 19 languages 
the japanese are not keen on books set in australia and the 
french dont like books set in france because they dont want 
anyone else writing about them whitehead said 
sally wentworths 43 books including the lord of misrule 
and wish on the moon have sold 15 million copies in 13 years 
but the audience gasped when wentworth confided that her success 
was preceded by 14 rejection letters 
wentworth said she writes 2000 words a day generating about 
four books a year she said she combs the birth columns of the 
conservative press for characters names such as verity charlotte 
and skye 
only a handful of men attended the seminar which isnt 
surprising only two of mills and boons stable of 300 permanent 
authors are male and they write under womens names 
dorothy minton 45 was waiting to hear mills and boons verdict 
on deceptively yours her third offering her first two were 
rejected with words of encouragement she declined to give away too 
much of the plot but said it was racier than the work of that 
other giantess of the genre barbara cartland 
minton took up writing when a medical problem with her shoulders 
forced her to give up her florist job her daughterinlaw fiona 
27 is spending her maternity leave writing the rainy day book 
under the pseudonym jinx moran and is on chapter three 
i want my baby to be late so i can finish it she said 
most of the aspiring writers want to make enough money to quit 
their daytime jobs or pay for an extra vacation or car 
whitehead said authors receive royalties of 4 percent of the 
paperback book profits the average paperback sells for 140 pounds 
230 less than half the price of an ordinary paperback 
among the most successful authors are wentworth charlotte lamb 
and penny jordan 
wentworth makes no claim to literary greatness 
mills and boon books are often looked down on and critics 
have no time for them she told the audience but they are 
extremely popular and the readers know exactly what they are 
getting and they will enjoy it 
