<TEXT>
during the winter season the club med sails the caribbean out 
of guadeloupe in the summer it will cruise the mediterranean out 
of ville franche on the french riviera 
designed by architect francois xavier poylo and built in le 
havre france the 100 million ship is owned by three french banks 
and leased to club med and service et transport a shipping firm 
for seven years with an option to buy 
at 617feet it is not the largest ship with sails in history 
the great eastern nearly a century and a half ago was 60 feet 
longer had propellers the size of windmills and stationed a bugler 
at the top of the companionway to summon her 4000 passengers to 
dinner a failure in the passenger trade she found glory as a 
giant sea spider spinning out the atlantic cable 
second mate heidenreich a sailing buff cites the cargo ship 
thomas lawson plying the maine coast at the turn of the century 
she had seven masts each named for a day of the week 
this ships top speed of 14 knots with an assist from her four 
dieselpowered electric turbines is sluggish compared with the 
great clipper ships like cutty sark and flying cloud which fully 
rigged with 28 sails rushed forty niners around the horn to the 
california gold rush at 20 knots 
but her creature comforts are a far cry from what club med 
offered poor french students and vacationing secretaries at its 
first tent village on majorca 40 years ago 
telephones tv hair dryers minibars kingsized beds and 
matisse prints grace the 204 cabins decorated by alberto pinto who 
did the gucci offices in milan and a royal yacht for prince kaled 
of saudi arabia 
there are two dining salons two outdoor pools a casino a 
beauty parlor sauna and a dutyfree boutique 
alas the tradition of a ships library has shrunk to a bookcase 
of paperbacks 
with a draft of only 15 feet this hitech windjammer can visit 
smaller islands and lonelier beaches a boulderstrewn cove called 
the baths on virgin gorda in the british virgin islands was 
scorned as too commercial because its pristine sands were 
interrupted by a beer tent and a stall selling tshirts 
on st thomas the beach was already occupied by a few thousand 
sailors from the us aircraft carrier enterprise enjoying their 
first shore leave in six months 
the exotic combination of a new fivemasted cruise ship anchored 
in the same harbor with a nuclear powered carrier begged the 
question of why this return to sail in the atomic age 
the japanese had experimented with saildriven tankers during a 
world oil crisis in the 70s and now said capt lambert they 
want to buy our software 
when mikhail gorbachev addressed the united nations a year and a 
half ago a soviet trade fair in new york exhibited models of a new 
generation of freighters with auxiliary sails two other 
computerized sailing ships about a third smaller are already in 
the cruise trade and more are on the drawing board 
this is not a romantic gimmick insists lambert under 
sail the ship is quieter more comfortable for passengers she 
rolls less there is no vibration with normal power we use 20 tons 
of marine diesel in 24 hours under full sail with our four 
generators also going we use 7 tons if the wind is from the 
starboard our computer directs the exhaust fumes off to port side 
even when there is very little wind the sails give us an 
extra 2 knots speed and every owner knows the last 2 knots are the 
most expensive 
the great clipper ships required a crew of 130 to wrestle with 
acres of canvas stretching 2990 square yards of dacron this 
latterday descendant needs only 35 officers and seamen not 
counting our most versatile hand the computer adds the captain 
