<TEXT>
the new head of the us border patrol believes 
illegal aliens looking for work should be treated with compassion 
even as they are turned back but when it comes to drug runners and 
other criminals mike williams is in favor of using the military to 
help seal the border some alien advocates disagree 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
for almost a quarter century mike 
williams has wrestled with the paradoxes of the nations southwest 
boundary an escape route for the destitute the front line of the 
nations war on drugs yet a doorway for commerce 
williams a border patrol agent who learned spanish from the 
illegal aliens he turned away is the agencys new chief 
williams was appointed in january to oversee the policing of 
some 5960 miles along the us borders with canada and mexico 
its a 263 millionayear operation involving 3800 border patrol 
agents in 22 districts 
williams says a good border patrol boss should know how to 
balance compassion for the illegal aliens looking for work in the 
united states with intolerance for the drug runners auto thieves 
alien smugglers and other sinister characters who defy the law 
i think that we dont need to apologize because we want to 
control our borders williams said in a recent interview as he 
completed his move to washington from el paso 
i think we need to recognize the sensitivity of the reasons 
why people come and we do but i dont think we need to say that 
we should not enforce laws 
williams also makes no apologies for controversial proposals to 
have the military help the border patrol fight illegal drug traffic 
i feel it is morally right to try to prevent this plague 
thats attacking america he says 
williams a native of gainesville fla began his border patrol 
career in 1967 after a fouryear stint with the coast guard at his 
first posting in comstock texas he learned the indian tracking 
techniques the patrol uses to pursue undocumented aliens often he 
would track them up to 70 miles inland though rugged country 
he says conversations with the illegal immigrants he arrested 
taught him spanish and developed his understanding of their 
hardships 
they come here to get jobs to feed their families to 
possibly increase their standard of living he says the worst 
thing that can happen to them is theyll get sent back to mexico 
so theyre going to come here to try to improve their standard of 
living 
williams demanded similar empathy from his officers when he 
headed the el paso border patrol sector says gus de la vina now 
its acting chief 
he taught the difference between dealing with a criminal vs 
dealing with a person that is coming in that is not a criminal but 
is violating an administrative law de la vina says 
jose guadalupe moreno director of the el paso catholic dioceses 
migrant and refugee services says he applauds the appointment of a 
border patrol chief who professes to understand the plight of 
immigrants but hes not sure that a law enforcement officer can be 
compassionate 
their job is to look for individuals who are here without 
documents moreno says no matter how professional they should 
be no matter what the policy it still takes the individual to 
follow through to act in a way that will not step all over 
peoples basic and human rights 
before coming to el paso the 45yearold williams headed the 
patrols office in havre mont and was deputy chief in san diego 
the largest border patrol sector 
williams says he has no hobbies spending most of his free time 
with the patrol when hes not home with his wife pat and their 
three children 
even before leaving el paso he was talking eagerly about the 
fight ahead to get more funding from congress 
its a challenge to me and ive always rode to the sound of 
the guns he said i feel i can make a difference that i can 
help these men and women that are out here on americas front line 
doing their job 
williams has taken on capitol hill before 
in 1986 he criticized congress for its sluggish pace rewriting 
immigration laws we are losing control of the border he said 
then 
the immigration and naturalization service believes the number 
of people crossing us borders illegally grows each year though 
there are no statistics other than the numbers caught 
and that number has dropped by half since the immigration reform 
and control act the law williams pushed for was passed in 1986 
it granted amnesty to about 3 million aliens who had lived in the 
country since 1982 and imposed sanctions on employers of 
undocumented workers 
in 1986 16 million aliens were arrested that fell to 855315 
in 1989 
border patrol officials figure that fewer arrests mean fewer 
people are trying to cross the border 
recently the number of arrests began to rise again patrol 
agents say they believe theyve controlled the exodus of central 
americans over the border but not mexicans 
critics such as brownsville immigration attorney linda yanez say 
thats a sure sign immigration reform is not working 
the purpose of much of the legislation was to curb and control 
immigration and it has not done that ms yanez says it just 
created more laws to punish and they dont work obviously were 
not addressing issues at their core 
the border patrol is moving into yet another arena of 
controversy as it takes on more duties in the war on drugs 
in fiscal 1989 the border patrol made 5441 drug seizures 
valued at 12 billion up from 3257 valued at 700 million the 
year before 
ms yanez says she is most concerned about proposals to use the 
military on the border i dont think it solves any problem and 
sends the wrong message she says 
but williams welcomes the additional manpower 
because of the magnitude of this influx of drugs were 
experiencing we welcome any assistance we can get he says 
they can be our eyes and ears out there when we dont have the 
manpower to be out there 
</TEXT>
