<TEXT>
pianist marcus roberts is traveling the jazz 
road laid down by the masters toward his own individuality 
i figure if youre going to learn how to play piano why 
wouldnt you listen to the music of thelonious monk or listen to 
duke ellington he says 
im interested in following a road that has been forged and 
set by the great masters of the art form that will lead me to the 
natural power of identity that i possess 
it is my feeling that if you have a concept of the tradition 
from which you come that can only strengthen your personal 
statement it is not going to limit your creativity to have studied 
30 great duke ellington compositions 
roberts who is blind has been receiving increasing attention 
and praise as pianist in trumpeter wynton marsalis group for the 
last five years he now has his second album on novus records 
deep in the shed referring to a place for intense practice and 
jazz experimentation it presents six tunes he composed and 
arranged each a different exploration of the blues 
i believe very strongly in playing blues any of the truly 
great jazz musicians play blues some nights duke ellington would 
play nine or 10 
the truth is spoken here roberts first album also on 
novus an rca records label had performances by drummer elvin 
jones and tenor saxophonist charlie rouse rouse played with 
monk elvin jones played with the great john coltrane i always 
had a great love for coltranes music it was an honor for me to be 
in the studio with him 
this record uses some of marsalis musicians and some unknowns 
who played dates with roberts last summer 
there are a lot of brilliant young musicians who deserve an 
opportunity to play whatever i can do to perpetuate that im 
going to do roberts said marsalis group is touring now 
roberts will start touring as a leader in may but he isnt really 
looking forward to doing that full time i like nothing better 
than to walk on wynton marsalis bandstand every night each day i 
have more love for him and his music its hard to picture myself 
not playing with him even though i know eventually that will 
probably happen 
he didnt always dream about leading his own combo roberts 
says first and foremost i just wanted to be part of a group of 
musicians that were all very serious and dedicated and who could 
all play 
i realized to get to a certain level of artistry it is 
necessary that you if possible try to establish your own vision 
and direction i guess over the years ive started to think more of 
having my own music and musicians 
the first time it came up was years ago wynton brought it up 
i hadnt been in his band very long he said whenever its time 
for you to go and do what you have to do know that ill 
understand i didnt know what he was talking about 
roberts is 26 nine years ago jazz pianist marian mcpartland 
was the first established performer to take an interest in him she 
was a judge in the first music competition he entered which he 
won i was in high school she gave me a lot of real good advice 
early on she represents what jazz music is all about she goes all 
over the place and does what she can to encourage young musicians 
to come out and play i have a great love for her 
he has been a guest on her piano jazz radio program 
she told me do as many records as you can document your 
music because thats the only way people ever remember who you are 
whatever you have to do no matter what the money is if you have 
music ready to be recorded get it recorded thats definitely 
some of the best advice ive ever been given by anybody said 
roberts who plans his third record as a solo piano of tunes by 
jelly roll morton ellington and monk 
when he cuts his own records robert said you have to 
determine everything concept music musicians the puzzle has to 
be in my mind and how the pieces should all fit together when i do 
records with wynton he is such an organized person all ive got 
to do is come in and play the piano 
marsalis first heard roberts in 1982 in chicago where he played 
as a student winner at a jazz educators convention he only heard 
me three more times before i joined his band he said 
we would stay in touch over the telephone wed talk he was 
never that impressed with my playing i was very very surprised 
when he asked me to join his band i always hoped it would happen 
there was not a band in the world i would have preferred to play 
with 
wyntons true greatness was not developed in the 80s in the 
90s people will really see the level of genius wynton has 
roberts who was born in jacksonville fla had cataracts as a 
youngster they operated when i was four or five that was that 
i did have some vision before 
he was named marthaniel when i was in elementary school i 
couldnt stand my name being butchered i thought of marcus i like 
marthaniel better but i dont like people mispronouncing it 
hes a graduate of florida state university earlier he 
attended a school for the blind in st augustine fla which had 
renowned piano teachers he already knew braille he composed a bit 
there a few little love songs for my girlfriends 
his spirit has not been sapped by his blindness 
my mother lost her sight when she was 15 she was able to keep 
me in the right track i couldnt say nobody understands 
