<TEXT>
growing numbers of older americans want to 
stay in their homes and never move but more than half have done 
little or no planning for their housing needs in later years a 
national survey shows 
the survey of 1500 people aged 55 and older commissioned by 
the american association of retired persons found that 86 percent 
wanted to age in place up from 78 percent in 1986 
fiftythree percent had done little or no planning for their 
housing those most likely to have done no planning were those over 
75 with less than 12000 annual income widowed divorced or 
never married and with health problems 
in general the people who have the strongest desire to stay 
put are also the most vulnerable the oldold the poor and the 
widowed the report said they are more likely to be forced out 
of their homes because of some crisis 
fortythree percent of older americans have lived in their homes 
for more than 20 years while only 17 percent have moved within the 
past five years of those who move 63 percent stay in the same 
city or county 
the survey found that 22 percent of older people expect to move 
but only 13 percent want to 
midlife and older people need to evaluate housing options 
before a crisis occurs the aarp said a lack of planning may 
force many older people out of their home against their wishes 
those who are willing to move especially the oldest respondents 
and those in poor health were more receptive to agesegregated 
housing than they were in aarps previous survey in 1986 forty 
percent prefer a senior citizens building to one for all age 
groups up from 32 percent in 1986 
the latest survey conducted in 1989 also found a growing 
expectation among the elderly that they will need help around their 
homes sixtyfive percent anticipate needing help with outside 
maintenance such as mowing lawns up from 40 percent in 1986 
fiftyfive percent expect to need help with heavy housework up 
from 33 percent 
individuals decision to move or stay may be influenced by how 
affordable reliable and accessible home and outdoor maintenance 
services become the aarp said 
the survey found that 23 percent of older people live alone 
with women those 75 and older and those with incomes below 12000 
most likely to do so five percent live in a retirement community 
or building planned for older adults twentyseven percent live in 
a neighborhood or building where a majority of the residents are 60 
or older 
the telephone survey was conducted by market facts inc in june 
1989 and had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage 
points results of the survey were released by the aarp this month 
</TEXT>
