<TEXT>
t franklin williams a geriatrics physician is 
director of the national institute on aging one of the 13 
institutes that comprise the national institutes of health of the 
department of health and human services 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the capacity and need for sexual expression 
continues into old age 
love and sex can be expressed in many ways the joy of 
companionship between two people can be shown by touching and 
holding hands caressing or by conversation and doing things 
together 
while some physical responses slow with age individuals of all 
ages can benefit both physically and psychologically by expressing 
their sexuality 
most older people want and can lead an active satisfying 
sex life indeed many 80 and 90yearold men and women have 
satisfying sexual relations 
with age women do not ordinarily lose their physical capacity 
for orgasm nor men their capacity for erecton and ejaculation 
there is often however a slowing of response 
for women changes that occur in the shape flexibility and 
lubrication of the vagina can usually be traced to lowered levels 
of the hormone estrogen during and after menopause many women say 
that after menopause when the fear of pregnancy and distractions 
of midlife have passed they become especially responsive sexually 
most healthy older men maintain their production of sex hormones 
at levels found in younger men however it usually takes an older 
man longer to achieve full erection 
although a pattern of regular sexual activity helps to preserve 
sexual ability research shows a gradual decline of sexual activity 
with age studies at the national institute on agings gerontology 
research center found that levels of sexual activity expressed in 
early adulthood usually predicted activity later in life 
overall health is of primary importance in maintaining sexual 
relationships in a study of 241 married men 60 and older 75 
percent of those without mobility problems reported they were 
sexually active while only 16 percent of those with mobility 
problems were 
even a serious disease rarely warrants stopping sexual 
relations one distressing myth is that sex is bad for your heart 
although cardiac patients should check with a doctor before 
resuming sexual activities generally the risk of a heart attack 
during sexual intercourse is about equal to the risk from climbing 
a flight of stairs 
several diseases such as arthritis can limit sexual activity 
depression a treatable disorder is one of the most common causes 
of altered sexual motivation 
diabetes is one of the few diseases that can cause impotence 
however once diabetes is diagnosed and controlled potency may be 
restored 
excessive use of alcohol which may reduce potency in men and 
delay orgasm in women is probably the most widespread drugrelated 
cause of sexual problems tranquilizers antidepressants and 
certain high blood pressure drugs may also cause impotence other 
drugs may reduce sexual desire 
almost everyone experiences a sexual problem at some time or 
another because sexual functioning is emotional and psychological 
as well as physical whats happening in the family or at work can 
have an important influence 
when problems occur they should not be viewed as a sign of 
aging but rather as the possible result of disease disability 
drug reactions or emotinal upset many sexual problems have 
emotional or organic causes that can be treated 
one barrier to a healthy sex life in old age stems from the 
disturbing myth that older people lose their sex appeal negative 
stereotypes are still too common any expression of sexual interest 
by an older woman who has no partner is typically viewed as 
unacceptable in our society the dirty old man who seeks sexual 
expression is the object of many jokes 
with the increasing lifespan and improvement of the overall 
health of older people sexual activity becomes an important aspect 
in overall quality of life 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
for a free copy of the age page sexuality in later life 
contact the national institute on aging information center po 
box 8057 gaithersburg md 208988057 additional information is 
available from the sex education information council of the united 
states 80 fifth ave suite 801 new york ny 10011 
2126733850 
</TEXT>
