<TEXT>
gulf i nuclear plant near port gibson miss a project that cost 
about six times more than original estimates 
middle south utilities built the plant and ordered its 
subsidiaries to share in the financing the costs then were passed 
on to consumers in the form of higher rates 
mississippi officials said consumers from their state are being 
forced to pay unfairly to help operate other nuclear plants in the 
middle south utilities system 
that argument was rejected by the federal energy regulatory 
commission when it adopted a rate formula for the four utilities 
the formula was pegged to each utilitys demand for electricity 
generated by the entire system 
mississippi officials said consumers there are helping pay for 
nuclear plants that supply no power to mississippians 
the us circuit court of appeals here last year upheld the 
commissions rate formula 
the appeals court said the commission properly allocated costs 
by basing them on overall demand by each utility and by taking into 
account that consumers in one state benefit indirectly from the 
systems nuclear units that only serve customers in the other 
states 
for example the appeals court said a nuclear plant in arkansas 
produces extra power available to be used by utilities from the 
other states 
the case is mississippi vs federal energy regulatory 
commission 891041 
