a federal bankruptcy judge on monday approved a 
plan that allows troubled general development corp to receive 
105 million in temporary financing for six weeks until it can 
arrange permanent financing 
general development already owes 175 million to the eight banks 
who guaranteed the interim financing according to a schedule 
submitted monday to us bankruptcy judge aj cristol 
each bank will put up a proportionate amount of the 105 
million based on the total owed to them under the plan submitted 
by attorneys for gdc and the banks and approved by cristol 
general development filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy april 6 
claiming a severe cash shortage after failing to secure 60 million 
in shortterm credit 
cristol heard objections from lawyers representing property 
owners from all over the united states who objected to a clause in 
the agreement under which gdc had to give the subscribing banks 
liens on the properties 
but lawyers for the property owners appeared satisfied when they 
were assured by attorneys for gdc and the banks that those who had 
paid in full for their property believed to number about 12000 
would not be encumbered with a bank lien when their deeds are 
delivered 
but they were reminded that as previously agreed the property 
owners might not get the same lot they paid for but might get one 
of equal or greater value in a portion of the development already 
built the company is not involved in property improvements for the 
time being 
attorneys for other property owners appeared skeptical 
if everybody works together this thing will work the judge 
told them the alternative is to see everything swept away 
the financing arrangement will expire june 1 and under the 
proposal it will be secured by a lien on all of gdcs assets 
including the collateral and all other real and personal property 
 
the collateral is identified as accounts receivable payments 
from property owners real estate and fixtures mortgages 
contracts and stock and various subsidiaries of general development 
cristol directed that the banks participating in the new 105 
million temporary loan should not be permitted to enhance their 
position in relation to other creditors 
cristols order says in part among other things entry of 
this order will minimize the disruption of gdcs businesses and 
operations as going concerns and will increase the possibility of a 
successful reorganization 
the entry of this order appears to be in the best interest of 
the debtors their creditors and the estates 
